**Idea:**

A more efficient way is to use a Binary Indexed Tree (or Fenwick Tree) to answer “range-sum” queries quickly. We first perform coordinate compression on the wealth values so that they fall within a small range. Then, while processing each merchant, we:


Convert his wealth to its compressed index.
Query the BIT to count how many merchants already in the hall have wealth greater than the current merchant.
Determine the rank as this count plus one.
Finally, update the BIT to include the current merchant.
**Complexity:**

With coordinate compression and BIT, each update and query takes O(log⁡N)O(\log N)O(logN) time, so the overall complexity becomes O(Nlog⁡N)O(N \log N)O(NlogN) which is efficient for the given constraints.

**C++ Implementation:**

`#include &lt;iostream&gt;
#include &lt;vector&gt;
#include &lt;algorithm&gt;
using namespace std;

struct Fenw {
    int n;
    vector&lt;int&gt; fenw;
    Fenw(int n): n(n) {
        fenw.assign(n + 1, 0);
    }
    void update(int i, int delta) {
        for (; i &lt;= n; i += i &amp; -i)
            fenw[i] += delta;
    }
    int query(int i) {
        int sum = 0;
        for (; i &gt; 0; i -= i &amp; -i)
            sum += fenw[i];
        return sum;
    }
};

int main() {
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);
    int N;
    cin &gt;&gt; N;
    vector&lt;int&gt; wealth(N);
    for (int i = 0; i &lt; N; i++) {
        cin &gt;&gt; wealth[i];
    }
    // Coordinate compression
    vector&lt;int&gt; sorted_wealth = wealth;
    sort(sorted_wealth.begin(), sorted_wealth.end());
    auto getIndex = [&amp;](int x) -&gt; int {
        return int(lower_bound(sorted_wealth.begin(), sorted_wealth.end(), x) - sorted_wealth.begin()) + 1;
    };
    int compSize = sorted_wealth.size();
    Fenw fenw(compSize);

    for (int i = 0; i &lt; N; i++) {
        int pos = getIndex(wealth[i]);
        int greater = fenw.query(compSize) - fenw.query(pos);
        int rank = greater + 1;
        cout &lt;&lt; rank &lt;&lt; "\n";
        fenw.update(pos, 1);
    }
    return 0;
}
`**Python Implementation:**

`def update(bit, i, delta, n):
    while i &lt;= n:
        bit[i] += delta
        i += i &amp; -i

def query(bit, i):
    s = 0
    while i:
        s += bit[i]
        i -= i &amp; -i
    return s

N = int(input().strip())
wealth = [int(input().strip()) for _ in range(N)]

# Coordinate compression
sorted_wealth = sorted(wealth)
comp = {v: i + 1 for i, v in enumerate(sorted_wealth)}
n_comp = len(sorted_wealth)
bit = [0] * (n_comp + 1)

for w in wealth:
    pos = comp[w]
    greater = query(bit, n_comp) - query(bit, pos)
    rank = greater + 1
    print(rank)
    update(bit, pos, 1, n_comp)
`**Idea:**

We can simulate a balanced binary search tree by maintaining a sorted list. In this approach, we use binary search (via `upper_bound` in C++ or the `bisect` module in Python) to determine the insertion position of the current merchant’s wealth in the sorted order. The number of merchants with greater wealth is the difference between the current length of the list and the insertion index. The rank is computed as this count plus one. After determining the rank, we insert the merchant’s wealth into the list in the correct position.

**Complexity:**

Finding the insertion position using binary search takes O(log⁡N)O(\log N)O(logN) time, but inserting into a sorted list takes O(N)O(N)O(N) time, so the worst-case complexity is O(N2)O(N^2)O(N2). This approach is straightforward and works well when the input size is moderate.

**C++ Implementation:**

`#include &lt;iostream&gt;
#include &lt;vector&gt;
#include &lt;algorithm&gt;
using namespace std;

int main(){
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);
    int N;
    cin &gt;&gt; N;
    vector&lt;int&gt; sortedList;
    for (int i = 0; i &lt; N; i++){
        int w;
        cin &gt;&gt; w;
        // Use upper_bound to find the insertion position in the sorted list (ascending order).
        auto it = upper_bound(sortedList.begin(), sortedList.end(), w);
        int pos = it - sortedList.begin();
        int count_greater = sortedList.size() - pos;
        int rank = count_greater + 1;
        cout &lt;&lt; rank &lt;&lt; "\n";
        sortedList.insert(it, w);
    }
    return 0;
}
